{"key":"processedPost-16294510","value":{"id":16294510,"first":16273818,"last":16298276,"when":1338220751,"utime":"05/28/12 06:59 PM","content":"I'd skip all that and just put a small humidifier in the bottom of the unit.&nbsp; Leave the flaps open or cut slits for fresh air.&nbsp; Once you have the shelves full, the humidity will be fine simply by misting, and that needs to be done by hand so you can adjust it as required for each tray.<br /><br />Your system of daisy chaining a hose between all the shelves won't work.&nbsp; You'll lose all your fog at the first set of holes.&nbsp; It's sort of like those soaker hoses you buy for garden use.&nbsp; All the water comes out in the first half of the hose, and the far end is dry.<br /><br />Also, remember that moist air is lighter than dry air, so in a closed up environment it's going to naturally rise to the top, leaving the bottom shelves at a lower humidity level.&nbsp; If you'll have plenty of openings in the greenhouse, natural air currents in the room will keep things stirred up.<br />RR","title":"Re: Fully Automated Greenhouse & Fogger Design; NEED FEEDBACK"}}